**Abstract:**
Extensive reading notes on Robert Kilwardby's "De Natura Theologiae" (Stegmuller edition, 1935). Kilwardby (c.1205-1279), Archbishop of Canterbury who proscribed Thomistic theses in 1277, represents Augustinian opposition to Aristotelico-Thomism. The document excerpts his treatment of theology's four causes, the nature of sacra scriptura as science, and the distinction between scientific knowledge (by human reason through definition, division, collection) and theological knowledge (by divine inspiration, moving affection through sapientia/gustus rather than just scientia/visus). Key source for understanding anti-Aristotelian positions.

**AI Recommendation:** Essential primary source notes on Kilwardby; documents the Augustinian critique of Aristotelian theology central to the Chantilly project.

